        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2436094268" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1571742566937241678">An autobiography more than anything, this is a candid and sympathetic story of the author&apos;s life, with an emphasis on his journey from a nominal muslim to a thoughtful and avowed atheist. I enjoyed very much the readable and winning style, the insight into the lives of others, and the contribution to the canon of atheist literature. Unlike perhaps some other ostensibly anti-religion books (&quot;The God Delusion&quot; for example), Shaha is not touting himself or what he writes as some superior moral auth</span>
  <span id="freeText1571742566937241678" style="display:none">An autobiography more than anything, this is a candid and sympathetic story of the author's life, with an emphasis on his journey from a nominal muslim to a thoughtful and avowed atheist. I enjoyed very much the readable and winning style, the insight into the lives of others, and the contribution to the canon of atheist literature. Unlike perhaps some other ostensibly anti-religion books ("The God Delusion" for example), Shaha is not touting himself or what he writes as some superior moral authority, which is nice, though I must say I found it a bit baffling when he talked about the eating of animals as something that we will look back on in the future and fail to justify morally, while all the same talking up the eating of animals in the present. </span>
