<div id="review_1281614307" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1281614307" />
    <a title="Jennifer Clark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28636191-jennifer-clark"><img alt="Jennifer Clark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512292235p2/28636191.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1281614307?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jennifer Clark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jennifer Clark" href="/user/show/28636191-jennifer-clark">Jennifer Clark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1281614307" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9128716481302379662">This wonderful book talks about the authors thoughts and feelings about the non existence of God and the freedom of life away from religion. I loved how he mixed in memoirs of his childhood growing up in a Bangladeshi muslin community in inner city London and how events shaped his views of non religion. The funny, sad and very honest story of his mother&apos;s death, relationships with his siblings and his abusive father would have made for an excellent autobiography of its own. The arguments for ath</span>
  <span id="freeText9128716481302379662" style="display:none">This wonderful book talks about the authors thoughts and feelings about the non existence of God and the freedom of life away from religion. I loved how he mixed in memoirs of his childhood growing up in a Bangladeshi muslin community in inner city London and how events shaped his views of non religion. The funny, sad and very honest story of his mother's death, relationships with his siblings and his abusive father would have made for an excellent autobiography of its own. The arguments for atheism won't be new to atheists reading this book and I'm not sure about its 'handbook' status (Shaha explains at the end of the book his reasons for this). Alom Shaha writes in such an accessible, easy way you can't help but like him - in fact I want to be his friend! I'd recommend this book to anyone over a Richard Dawkins' God Delusion (who I find comes accross as a bit of a nasty bastard!). 5 stars and hooray for atheists!</span>
  <a data-text-id="9128716481302379662" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


